[recursive vs. distributed polynomials]
> I don't know how we should model "abstract polynomials", but I'm not ev=
en sure
> whether we should have such a thing.

That would be possible, but suppose you want to do a Gr=F6bner basis=20
computation. Who is going to choose the most efficient data representatio=
n?

In fact, one could model that, but where should it be stored?

The GB algorithm could only make some statements about "I probably run=20
fastest with this and that representation", but the "abstract=20
polynomials" might not provide such a representation. What to do then?

Or you could store the knowledge that "for GB computations this or that=20
representation is best" in the "abstract polynomials". Then somebody=20
comes and adds a knew algorithm to the system and the "abstract=20
polynomials" just don't know about the appropriate representation.

I think it is totally hard to map the mathematical concept of=20
polynomials to just ONE "abstract polynomial" type and make the choice=20
of the underlying datastructure invisible.

> Concerning provisos, this really affects only the domain EXPR, in my op=
inion.

Provisos look to me like a tree of results stored in one object. But=20
maybe I should read Tim's thesis first.

Anyway, yesterday I spoke with Antoine Hersen about provisos.
He came up with the following simple system in Q[x,y].

x*y =3D b
a*x =3D b

With provisos, I guess we are speaking about polynomials in Q(a,b)[x,y]=20
where we are looking for a solution in some extension of Q depending on=20
the parameters a and b.

As we all know, the result of the second equation splits into 4 cases=20
depending on whether a and/or b is 0. And the result is best described=20
by the set of solutions together with the conditions.

To make it simple the type would be

(subset of Q, equations/elements in Q(a,b))

and all 4 cases live in just ONE proviso? (Maybe I missed something.)
Anyway. Now solve the first equation. Interestingly, the type would be

(subset Q(x), equations in Q(a,b,x)),

since if a=3Db=3D0 you cannot say anything about x.

The question is: What type should provisos have? See, I start with=20
Q(a,b)[x,y] in the beginning. How do I know that I will need Q(a,b,x) in =

the result?

Ralf





